post_text:
People with heart or lung disease, older adults, children and teens – take any of these steps to reduce your exposure:

• Avoid strenuous outdoor activities.
• Keep outdoor activities short.
• Consider moving physical activities indoors or rescheduling them.

Everyone else – take any of these steps to reduce your exposure:

• Choose less strenuous activities (like walking instead of running) so you don’t breathe as hard.
• Shorten the amount of time you are active outdoors.
• Be active outdoors when air quality is better.

Happy Ethiopian New Year! Ethiopia rings in its new year, Enkutatash, also known as "gift of jewels” on September 11. It marks the end of the rainy season when bright autumn days return with adey abeba flowers (yellow daisies), which are seen everywhere in Ethiopia. Children usually give these flowers to their elders in exchange for a blessing, bread or money. The holiday typically last an entire week and consists of family gatherings, food, singing, dancing and more.

post_text: Students and local fish will have an easier time navigating Juanita Creek thanks to a new pedestrian bridge installed in August. The bridge connects a trail along the south edge of Juanita High School that is used frequently by community members. Before the bridge was available, pedestrians crossed the creek on wooden boards. As part of the design and planning for the rebuilt and enlarged school, Lake Washington School District collaborated with the City of Kirkland and the Washington Department of Fish & Wildlife on the project.

post_text:
The College Board has new ordering deadlines, late fees and cancellation fees. To meet the College Board ordering deadlines, Lake Washington School District students will register for AP exams from September 1, 2020 to the end of the last lunch on September 25. The payment window for all exams will be October 1, 2020 through October 30, 2020. We encourage all students wanting to take May 2021 AP exams to complete the registration and pay for their exams during this registration window. CollegeBoard has suspended the cancellation fee for the 2020-21 school year. Students may cancel an exam at any time throughout the course!

For students that may still be deciding in October if they want to take AP exams in May, LWSD is offering a LATE AP Exam Registration window from February 1, 2021 through end of last lunch on February 19, 2021. Students who register during the late AP Registration window will incur a $50 per exam late fee in addition to the $96 per exam fee.

Read more about the AP exam registration: bit.ly/APRegistration20

post_text: LWSD is committed to providing access to all individuals seeking information on our website, including persons with disabilities. In September 2020, LWSD adopted AudioEye, a leading Web accessibility solution, to ensure that people with disabilities have equal access to the information on our websites and to meet the requirements of the Americans With Disabilities Act. Lake Washington School District is offering free meals to all children ages 1-18, starting Tuesday, September 1.

Lake Washington School District added a new photo to the album: 2020 COVID-19 Announcements.
July 9 at 2:43 PM ·

COVID-19 numbers in King County have increased dramatically. A majority of the cases are among young people ages 20-39. Please know COVID-19 can still be dangerous for people of all ages, including young people. Anyone can still infect others through community transmission. It is predicted that the situation will become more challenging as we enter this coming fall and winter.

Help stop the spread of COVID-19 by following the guidelines from Public Health - Seattle & King County:

- Wear a face covering when in public.
- Wash your hands often or use hand sanitizer.
- Stay six feet apart from one another when in public.
- Avoid gatherings with people outside your household.
- Cover your coughs and sneezes.
- Clean and sanitize regularly, especially frequently touched surfaces.
- Get tested at the first sign of illness.

For more information about COVID-19 updates and recommendations, visit the Seattle & King County Public Health website at: kingcounty.gov/covid

Cleaning and disinfecting high touch surfaces can help stop the spread of COVID-19. This include tables, doorknobs, light switches, counter tops, handles, desks, phones, keyboards, toilet faucets, sinks, etc. First use soap and water to reduce the number of germs, dirt and impurities on the surface. Then apply disinfectant to the surface, which kills the germs. Wash your hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.

- You can also call the King County 24-Hour Crisis Line at 1-866-427-4747 for professional mental health services and support.

Lake Washington School District added a new photo.
July 23 at 9:05 PM ·

All Lake Washington School District (LWSD) students (grades Preschool-12) will be starting the 2020-21 school year learning in a fully remote setting.

Over the last week Superintendent Dr. Jon Holmen has been actively engaged with a number of entities as we evaluate our plans for school in the fall. As of today, LWSD will start the 2020-21 school year learning in a fully remote setting.

This decision is being made after a thorough review of available reports and local models. Additionally, Dr. Holmen and staff spent time discussing the current state of our community and county with the King County Department of Health. Given this and the limited guidance districts have received related to re-opening school in the fall; it was decided to start the school year in a remote model.

To read the full announcement, visit the LWSD website at: bit.ly/R2SRemote

COVID-19 spreads mainly among people who are in close contact (within about 6 feet) for a prolonged period. Spread happens when an infected person coughs, sneezes or talks and droplets from their mouth or nose are launched into the air and land in the mouths or noses of people nearby. Since people can spread the virus before they know they are sick, it is important to stay at least 6 feet away from others when possible, even if you—or they—do not have any symptoms.

For more information about COVID-19 updates and recommendations, visit the Public Health - Seattle & King County website at: kingcounty.gov/covid or the Center for Disease Control (CDC) website at: www.cdc.gov

The state now requires people in Washington to wear face coverings in public places. Face coverings limit the transmission of droplets that could spread COVID-19. When you wear a face covering, you protect your loved ones and those around you.

Help stop the spread of COVID-19 by following the guidelines from Public Health - Seattle & King County:

- Wear a face covering when in public.
- Wash your hands often or use hand sanitizer.
- Stay six feet apart from one another when in public.
- Avoid gatherings with people outside your household.
- Cover your coughs and sneezes.
- Clean and sanitize regularly, especially frequently touched surfaces.
- Get tested at the first sign of illness.

For more information about COVID-19 updates and recommendations, visit the Seattle & King County Public Health website at: kingcounty.gov/covid

shared_text:
Lake Washington Schools Foundation
July 3 at 1:41 AM ·

LWSD students and sisters, Vanesha Hari and Varshini Hari co-founded a nonprofit initiative called Joys of Giving which was established to bring hope, opportunity, and resources to those in need.

When COVID-19 struck our community, they saw the need to raise funds to provide food, mental health support, and educational opportunities. They learned that the Lake Washington Schools Foundation would become the perfect fit and have directed $2,000 to support the LWSD community!

Visit www.lwsf.org/teensmakingadifference to learn more about all of their great work in the community!

Thank you Vanesha and Varshini for supporting local students, especially during these challenging and uncertain times. We hope that your story will inspire others to be just as caring as you are!

- Wear a face covering when in public.
- Wash your hands often or use hand sanitizer.
- Stay six feet apart from one another when in public.

- Clean and sanitize regularly, especially frequently touched surfaces.

July 9 at 2:43 PM ·

COVID-19 numbers in King County have increased dramatically. A majority of the cases are among young people ages 20-39. Please know COVID-19 can still be dangerous for people of all ages, including young people. Anyone can still infect others through community transmission. It is predicted that the situation will become more challenging as we enter this coming fall and winter.

Help stop the spread of COVID-19 by following the guidelines from Public Health - Seattle & King County:

- Wear a face covering when in public.
- Wash your hands often or use hand sanitizer.
- Stay six feet apart from one another when in public.
- Avoid gatherings with people outside your household.
- Cover your coughs and sneezes.
- Clean and sanitize regularly, especially frequently touched surfaces.
- Get tested at the first sign of illness.

For more information about COVID-19 updates and recommendations, visit the Seattle & King County Public Health website at: kingcounty.gov/covid

Rose Hill Middle School Band Instructor, Angela Laulainen got creative during the remote learning period and had her students record their parts at home. The audio, video and image files then got edited together by Arts Laureate into virtual performances.

When schools closed in March, the traditional end-of-year band concerts that showcase a year’s worth of practice and progress were effectively canceled. Rose Hill Middle School Band Instructor, Angela Laulainen got creative during the remote learning period and had her students record their parts at home. The audio, video and image files then got edited together by Arts Laureate into virtual performances.

post_text:
Looking for a preschool for next year? Registration is now available for Lake Washington School District’s (LWSD) preschool programs for the 2020-21 school year.

LWSD Preschool Programs focus on providing children and families with a successful first-school experience. Families with a 3- and/or 4-year-old child living within the boundaries of LWSD are eligible to apply for the preschool program. (Child must be 3-years-old by August 31 of the school year.)

If you are interested in applying, please visit our Preschool page on the LWSD website at www.lwsd.org/preschool

Lake Washington School District Families: We want to hear from you! Our Return to School Task Force is considering a hybrid rotation model for grades 2-12 at the start of the 2020-21 school year. All preschool, kindergarten and first-grade students would attend school each day. This hybrid model would combine in-person class time with virtual, distance-learning time. Please fill out our survey asking families for their preferences within this hybrid model as well as questions about interest in a full remote learning option. To take the survey, visit: bit.ly/R2SHybridModel

Students at Rockwell Elementary spent time this spring writing notes of appreciation to share just how grateful they are to City of Redmond, Washington -Government workers. Students thanked the workers for continuing to work during the global pandemic.

“I am very grateful that you are still working and keeping our town’s trees and shrubs trimmed,” wrote one student to the Parks and Recreation Department. “You are keeping us and our environment safe. I want you to know that we appreciate all your efforts and that you are doing amazing work. I hope that you feel noticed and have a fantastic day.”

Read more: bit.ly/RockwellCOR

In addition, Redmond High School’s Sanjali Vuriti received an honorable mention in the competition.

Congratulations, Sophia and Sanjali!

post_text: Join us on a virtual tour of the Early Learning Center at the Old Redmond Schoolhouse led by our LWSD design and construction team. Last year, envelope enclosure concerns on this nearly 100 year old historic building required us to perform additional maintenance on the roof, windows and exterior face of the building. Interior renovations will provide 10 early learning classrooms, office space, resource library for parents, community gathering room, therapy & motor skills rooms, a parent support library, and teacher planning / work rooms. We are ecstatic to provide a historic educational space for our youngest scholars at Lake Washington School District. Thank you to the entire community for your support!

June 18 at 4:14 PM ·

Lake Washington School District (LWSD) has developed a facility re-opening timeline that is in accordance with Washington's Safe Start phased approach. As King County, Washington - Government meets requirements to move into each phase, LWSD will reopen our athletic facilities in accordance with guidance from the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and Public Health - Seattle & King County.

Tennis courts at our middle school and high school have been open since June 11. Tracks will be open for walking and jogging when King County is in Phase 2. Fields will remain closed. We will update our communities as more of our facilities open to the public.

Please remember to put safety first when gathering to play. LWSD urges visitors to practice social distancing and good hygiene and to follow Public Health - Seattle and King County Guidelines.

For more information, visit: bit.ly/LWSDFacilities

post_text: We could not provide an in-person retirement celebration this year, so instead we have created a presentation honoring all of the retirees from the 2019-20 school year. We want to thank all of our retirees for their years of tireless work with the district and we wish them luck on whatever retirement holds for them.

Looking for a preschool for next year? Registration is now available for LWSD preschool programs for the 2020-21 school year.

LWSD Preschool Programs focus on providing children and families with a successful first-school experience. Families with a 3- and/or 4-year-old child living within the boundaries of LWSD are eligible to apply for the preschool program. (Child must be 3 years old by August 31 of the school year.)

If you are interested in applying, please visit our Preschool page on the LWSD website at lwsd.org/preschool

post_text: We are excited to share the construction progress at Juanita High School through a virtual tour led by our LWSD design and construction team. Juanita High School is scheduled to complete its final phase this fall, which also means we will complete our new rebuild and enlarge facility one full school year ahead of schedule. JHS Phase 2 includes CTE classroom and lab spaces, bus loop, courtyard and connection areas to Phase 1 (general classrooms, administrative offices, career/counseling centers, theatre, commons and food services). Thank you to the entire community for your support!

Thank you to the entire community for your support!

post_text: A gift that continues to give! Earlier this month, Clara Barton Elementary surprised crews and volunteers at the Open Kitchen Redmond with coffee and treats. This was made possible by the coordination of Mrs. Lovatt, Barton’s school counselor, Myla Rugge, a Barton parent and staff at a local Starbucks. During this school closure, Open Kitchen Redmond has been serving our students and families by donating food boxes. The team is currently renewing their efforts in order to raise money to support our families during the summer. Thank you, Open Kitchen!

post_text:
Your children may also be eligible for a new food assistance program called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT). P-EBT provides families with funds to make up the cost of meals while school was closed. This benefit is for ALL children in Washington who receive free or reduced-price school meals. These benefits will be on an Electronic Benefits Transfer (EBT) card which is used like a debit card to buy groceries.

For additional Information about the P-EBT Program, visit the OSPI website here: k12.wa.us/PEBT

Thanks to a waiver that was approved on June 10 by the USDA, LWSD will be able to continue serving free meals during the summer. These meals are federally funded and available to any child ages 1-18.

We will continue our current operation of Grab & Go meals at the six middle school sites as well as the pick-up locations through August 7, 2020. Meals will not be provided during the week of June 29 – July 5 due to the Fourth of July holiday. The number of pick-up locations is subject to change.

For more information, visit the district website at lwsd.org/meals

Tennis courts at our middle school and high school are now open! In accordance with city, county and state guidance, we have opened up the tennis courts to the public at our middle and high school sites, where available. Just a reminder that large, organized activities are not allowed on the courts in the current re-opening phase, and play is limited to groups of 5 or fewer if they don’t live in the same household. Please remember to put safety first when gathering to play. We will update our communities as more of our facilities open to the public.

post_text: NASA astronaut Anne McClain has done quite a bit in the last year and a half. She spent nearly seven of those months aboard the International Space Station (ISS). That trip included two spacewalks where nothing but space came between her and the Earth below her. In March 2019, while still aboard the ISS, she spent about an hour speaking to students at Thoreau Elementary School. Since then she has been staying active with NASA and looking forward to events like the May SpaceX flight. Story: bit.ly/ThoreauNASA

post_text: To say the least, Molly Williams is an accomplished wrestler. The Redmond High School (RHS) senior capped her high school career with a state championship in the 115-pound weight division in February. She compiled a career record of 142-23, which according to her coach makes her one of only two 100+ match winners in RHS history. She placed at state in all four years capturing seventh, fifth and third, respectively. She is a two-time WIAA state Athlete of the Week award winner. Williams is also a Cadet All-American and a Junior All American. Read more: bit.ly/RHSWilliams

post_text:
A Message for our Rosa Parks Community:

This afternoon, a piece of pressure washer equipment working on the roof of Rosa Parks experienced an equipment failure, causing a fire. The fire department responded, and everyone is safe. We did experience damage to our roof that they are currently working to fix. We are asking that all of our families and community members stay off campus, so that the fire department and our Support Services staff can work on this issue.

Due to the extended school closures, LWSD will be offering 2020 summer programs primarily to support students in grades K-3 who are not reading at grade level, high school students who may need additional credits towards on-time graduation, and students who need Special Education Services. Families will be notified this week if they are eligible for these programs.

The exception will be the accelerated math courses that allow students to move more quickly through the LWSD math pathways resulting in higher-level math options in their junior and senior years of high school. Families who are interested in participating in this program should register on the LWSD website: bit.ly/LWSDSummer20

May 30 at 12:21 AM ·

Meet Kristin Bauer, our counselor at Norman Rockwell Elementary! Here's her wellness tip for the day:

"Focus on the things you can control, and let go of worrying about the things you can’t control. We often spend a lot of time and energy worrying about things we cannot change, which just ends up draining us mentally and emotionally. Instead, put your time and energy into things you can control, such as how you take care of yourself, the time you spend with your family, your own attitude and giving grace to yourself and others."

post_text:
LWSD will offer summer programs to support our most at-risk learners, including high school students who may need additional credits towards on time graduation and students in kindergarten through third grade who are not reading at grade level. Summer school offerings will mainly be conducted remotely with ongoing support from certificated and classified staff.

We will also offer accelerated math courses that allow student to move more quickly through the LWSD math pathways resulting in higher-level math options in their junior and senior years of high school.

Students will access summer school in different ways depending on their specific learning needs.

More information will be shared with families directly on Tuesday, June 2, 2020.

Meet Jayme BranaghLandon, our counselor at Benjamin Rush Elementary! Here's her wellness tip for the day:

“Set boundaries and prioritize. Many of us have work, family and school demands. Some of us have children and in some cases, multiple children in multiple schools. It is impossible to manage everything all the time. Set boundaries when you can. Be realistic with what can be accomplished. Some things will have to wait until the next day.

Make time for yourself. Can you take a few minutes to be alone? Take your dog for a walk, step out on your patio or deck and make time to read. Create your own space or routine, even if it is just a few short moments.

By taking time for yourself, you will find the ability to handle the stress and demands just a little easier."

Meet Katie Epstein, our counselor at Samantha Smith Elementary! Here's her wellness tip for the day:

"Head outdoors! Being in natural environments has a way of relaxing and de-stressing the body and mind. Going for a walk, run, bike ride or any outdoor activity of interest can boost your energy, strengthen your heart and increase your immune system. My personal favorite is running with my dog. Plus, I love to get out in the garden as well. What is your favorite thing to do outdoors?"

post_text: Two students from International Community School took on the topic of gender equality in a recent essay contest. It paid off for both of them as Julia Lee and Santoshi Pisupati took home second and third place, respectively. The World Citizen Essay contest is hosted by the World Affairs Council. The organization advances global understanding and engagement throughout the Puget Sound region.

post_text: Three high school students from Redmond High School (RHS) have discovered a unique opportunity to help others study and raise money for COVID-19 relief. RHS juniors Dania Ahmed, Ashley Chiu and Emily Deng started a youth-led nonprofit organization called Review for Relief. The team has put together additional study guides for AP students in exchange for a donation to global COVID-19 relief efforts. Already, Review for Relief has raised $5,000 through their GoFundMe page! Read more: bit.ly/RHSRelief

Public Health - Seattle & King County
May 11 at 10:00 PM ·

Starting May 18, King County residents are directed to wear face coverings in most public settings.

Wear a face covering when you are at any indoor or outdoor public space where you may be within 6 feet of someone who does not live with you.

A face covering is not needed when you are outside walking, exercising, or otherwise outdoors if you are able to regularly stay 6 feet away from other people who do not live with you.

Visit kingcounty.gov/masks to learn more and find information about face coverings in additional languages.

post_text:
Looking for a preschool for next year? Registration is now available for Lake Washington School District’s (LWSD) preschool programs for the 2020-21 school year.

LWSD Preschool Programs focus on providing children and families with a successful first-school experience. Families with a 3- and/or 4-year-old child living within the boundaries of LWSD are eligible to apply for the preschool program. (Child must be 3-years-old by August 31 of the school year.)

If you are interested in applying, please visit our Preschool page on the LWSD website at www.lwsd.org/preschool

Meet Shannon Leonard, our librarian at Horace Mann Elementary!

Her book recommendation is “'Rescue & Jessica" by Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes. Here’s what she shared about her favorite book:

"I would like to recommend this award-winning picture book, 'Rescue & Jessica' by Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes. Rescue & Jessica, is an inspiring true story of Boston Marathon survivors, Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes. The heart of the story lies not in the tragedy of that day, but rather the steps made to recover and rebuild a wonderful life with the help of Rescue, Jessica’s service dog. Rescue and Jessica is also a contender for the 2021 Washington Children's Choice Picture Award."

post_text: Today LWSD Superintendent, Dr. Jane Stavem, visited Finn Hill Middle School to recognize our Nutrition Services staff in honor of School Lunch Hero Day. The Kirkland Police and Fire Departments also paid a special visit to thank our team. Through April 27, LWSD had served 52,786 meals to children at 35 locations! To our Nutrition Services team at LWSD, thank you for working on the front line to ensure every child has the food they need during our school closures. Not all heroes wear capes — ours wear aprons!

Meet Gretchen Oates, our librarian at Robert Frost Elementary.

Her book recommendation is "Mother Bruce” by Ryan T. Higgins. Here’s what she shared about her favorite book:

“I absolutely love books by Ryan T. Higgins! His books are funny and they have colorful, cute illustrations. In ‘Mother Bruce,’ Bruce is a very grumpy bear who likes to cook fancy egg recipes. Unfortunately, the newest eggs he just gathered end up hatching and Bruce finds he is now the ‘mama’ to four baby goslings. I love the creative ways Bruce tries to adapt to his new life with the geese.”

Meet Heather Jones, our librarian at Redmond Elementary!

Her book recommendation is "Lost in the Library” by Josh Funk. Here’s what she shared about her favorite book:

“This book is about two lions named Patience and Fortitude, who sit on the steps at the entrance of the New York Public Library. They guard the building during the day. By night, these precocious lions sneak into the library to read the books! I found this book in the gift shop at the New York Public Library while helping my daughter get her first library card as a new student living in New York City.”

Congratulations to Carl Sandburg Elementary and Discovery Community School! On Earth Day, April 22, the U.S. Department of Education announced that the two schools, which share a building, are among the 2020 U.S. Department of Education Green Ribbon Schools award honorees.

Principal Lori Pierce congratulated the school community in a video announcement. She was joined by LWSD Superintendent Dr. Jane Stavem, Elizabeth Schmitz from the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI), and Brian Goodman from California Casualty.

More: bit.ly/LWSDGreenRibbon

Schools in Washington stand out for closing gaps, showing growth, and demonstrating achievement according to new data released by the state.

Twenty of the schools being recognized come from Lake Washington School District (LWSD). Here is a list of the LWSD schools recognized by the state and what they are being recognized for: bit.ly/LWSDSBE

In the fall, the Green Team at Ella Baker Elementary School learned that students were not correctly sorting compost and recyclables during lunch. When too many materials are incorrectly sorted, the utility has to throw all of it into the trash.

The Green Team took quick action. They weighed the cafeteria waste in September and found that 100 pounds of lunch waste was going into the trash daily. In October, they made educational announcements and 3-D signs so students were aware of the problem and could see visually what should go where.

Green Team students and parent volunteers helped students learn to sort their lunch waste correctly. Now, food waste (compostables) account for about 70 pounds of lunch waste. Recyclables are about 10 pounds. About 20 pounds is going to the landfill each day. That’s 80 pounds less than when they started.

When school starts again, the Green Team plans to focus on reducing food waste.

Meet Jim Anderson, our librarian at Rosa Parks Elementary!

His book recommendation is "To Market, To Market” by Nikki McClure. Here’s what he shared about his favorite book:

“‘To Market, To Market’ is a book that can be enjoyed by everyone. It combines beautiful pictures with meaningful words. Nikki McClure uses her unique cut-paper illustrations to tell a story about a mother and son and their weekly visits to a farmer’s market. As they check off items on their shopping list, readers will learn how each particular food was grown or produced, from its earliest stages to how it ended up at the market. This book explores themes including community, nutrition, hard work and living gentle on the planet. Nikki lives in Olympia, which gives the book a Northwest feel.”

You’re registered 4 SchoolMessenger notifications. Reply STOP to cancel, HELP for help. Msg&data rates may apply. Msg freq varies. Schoolmessenger.com/txt.

LWSD to Honor Seniors With #BeTheLightWA on Friday, April 17:

On Friday, April 17, Lake Washington School District, like many school districts across the state of Washington, will be turning on our high school stadium lights at 8:20 p.m. (20:20 military time) for 20 minutes in a symbolic gesture to honor the graduating class of 2020.

Since our school campuses are still closed under the Governor’s “Stay Home, Stay Safe” order, we will be taking pictures of our stadiums lit up to honor our seniors across the school district, and sharing them out on social media so that our community can experience this recognition virtually.

We invite you to join us in spirit only, knowing that we are not able to gather on campus. We ask that people not come to our campuses and we will have security on site to prevent people from entering parking lots and gathering.

We will continue to look for ways to recognize the class of 2020 that comply with the Governor's guidelines. Thank you for your support and cooperation.

post_text:
As soon as the first school closures were announced, the staff and community at Redmond Elementary began a food drive to ensure no students would go hungry. In addition to the weekly Pantry Packs, 70 families have been receiving supplementary food boxes each Tuesday, assembled from donations from our school community and community partners.

Families who are unable to pick up are receiving weekly deliveries, ensuring safety and social distancing measures are observed.

If your children are experiencing stress or anxiety, remind them that adults are working to address this concern, and give them actions that they can take to protect themselves. Encourage them to stay home to stay healthy and to practice good hygiene:

1. Wash hands multiple times a day for at least 20 seconds. (Sing Twinkle, Twinkle Little Star slowly, which takes about 20 seconds.)

2. Cover mouth with a tissue when sneezing or coughing and throw the tissue away immediately. Another option is to sneeze or cough into the bend of an elbow.

3. Stay at least six feet apart from people when in public.

Visit the cdc.gov for more tips on basic hygiene and healthy lifestyle practices.

Meet Liz Haggerty, our librarian at Kirkland Middle School!

Her book recommendations are ‘This Was Our Pact’ by Ryan Andrews and ‘What I Carry’ by Jennifer Logo. Here’s what she shared about her favorite books:

"‘What I Carry’ is about a girl named Muiriel who is about to age out of the foster care system and she is determined to not build any relationships before then. Until she meets Francine and Kira, she gets the perfect job and meets Sean. It’s a beautiful and sad story and it’s written in honor of the author’s daughter who came to her from foster care.

‘This Was Our Pact’ is about a group of boys who have always been told the lanterns that are released once a year in their town’s river turn into stars. They decide this year they are going to find out if this is true or not. What they find is more magical than they dreamed.”

“On the night before the ceremony in which Tiuri is to be knighted, he is commissioned by a dying man to deliver a letter that might save his kingdom from doom. In accepting this secret quest, Tiuri loses his chance to be knighted. But the quest is just the kind of chivalrous act a knight would never turn down, so Tiuri accepts it and sets out on his journey. A story of action, mystery, intrigue, adventure, unseen enemies and friends in unexpected places, 'The Letter for the King' is a book I recommend to any middle or high school student!”

How much information should we share with our children about COVID-19?

Let your children’s questions be your guide as to how much information to provide. You can listen to their concerns, fears and questions, but try to keep your responses factual and age appropriate to lower their stress and anxiety levels.

Remind them that adults are working to address this concern, and give them actions that they can take to protect themselves. This includes staying home, washing hands and keeping six feet apart from people when in public.

For additional facts, check out: cdc.gov
For more tips on talking points, visit: bit.ly/NASPCOVID

Lake Washington School District added a new photo.
April 8 at 5:51 PM ·

Meet Stephanie Johnson, our librarian at Ella Baker Elementary!

Her book recommendation is “The One and Only Ivan” by Katherine Applegate. Here’s what she shared about her favorite book:

"This book is the winner of the 2013 Newbery Medal for the most distinguished contribution to American literature for children. In this sweet story, narrated by Ivan the gorilla, readers will be brought into Ivan’s life in captivity, where he spent the past 27 years behind a glass enclosure in a shopping mall. There he watches television, paints and hangs out with his friends, Stella and Bob. But when a baby elephant named Ruby comes to join his enclosure, he begins to see his time at the mall through Ruby’s eyes. Ivan becomes very protective of Ruby and realizes that things need to change for the better. Katherine Applegate creates an unforgettable first-person narration of hope and friendship."

From Monday through Friday, LWSD is offering free breakfast and lunches to any child 18 and under. Pre-order your meal now until tomorrow at 8 a.m. Visit the district website at: www.lwsd.org/meals

Meals can be picked up at the same time between 10:30 a.m. - 12 p.m. from six middle schools: Finn Hill, Inglewood, Kamiakin, Redmond, Rose Hill, and Timberline.

If you miss the order window, you can still get a meal! Just visit one of our sites.

March 19 at 10:07 PM ·

To help support families during the school closure due to the Coronavirus, Lake Washington School District is committed to providing healthy and nutritious meals to any child 18 and under for free. Monday-Friday, LWSD is offering breakfast and lunches that can be picked up at the same time.

Meals can be picked up at six middle schools: Finn Hill, Inglewood, Kamiakin, Redmond, Rose Hill, and Timberline.

Visit www.lwsd.org/meals to pre-order by 8 a.m. If you miss the order window, you can still get a meal! Just visit one of our sites.

Pantry Packs will have volunteers at each location on Friday, March 20, to provide meals for the weekend for any students who need one. For more information about the Pantry Packs program, please visit: www.lwsf.org/pantrypacks

shared_text:
Lake Washington School District added a new photo.
March 13 at 12:16 AM ·

Lake Washington School District is committed to supporting our children and community through these unprecedented times. Today, Governor Inslee announced that all schools in King, Snohomish and Pierce counties will need to close their schools until April 24. This extends our original March 27 closure date by nearly an additional month.

We recognize that this disruption in our normal school day and school year has an impact on our students, our families and our staff. We know that this exceptional moment has prompted lots of conversation and questions which we will address in the coming days.

Our staff has been finalizing plans to provide for nutrition services, educational opportunities and emergency supervision during this time period.

We expect to be able to provide more details tomorrow regarding services and we appreciate your patience as our staff transitions to support our students in very different ways than we have before.

post_text: Students at Horace Mann Elementary School are spicing it up in the kitchen. Those participating in the Rainy Day Dinner Club at the school recently made Jambalaya to take home to their families. The club met every Wednesday for five weeks in January and early February learning how to chop vegetables, add spices and put it all together for a delicious meal. The goal of the after school class is to help students develop a new relationship with cooking by using fresh ingredients and trying new flavors.

On January 25, middle school students across LWSD battled it out in the kitchen as they competed for culinary supremacy. Twenty-six teams were given a recipe for fried rice with only 45 minutes to prepare the dish. Teams were judged on how well they followed the recipe, knife skills, sanitation and overall cooking. Congrats to the following winners!

FIRST PLACE: FIRST ROUND
- Jasmine Zhen, International Middle School
- Lexi Sevigny, Evergreen Middle School

The project is a result of Engrossed Substitute House Bill 1109 passed by the state Legislature which provided $25,000,000 to the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI) to implement professional development in support of inclusionary practices in schools and districts. The state Legislature, OSPI and LWSD have made it a priority to provide more students with disabilities access to learn in general education settings with their non-disabled peers. Read more: bit.ly/LWSDInclusionary

We need your input! What are the most important perspectives to consider as we plan for future facilities to accommodate growth in our district?

We need your input on planning for future facilities to accommodate growth in our district to share with our Facility Advisory Committee (FAC), so we can learn what’s most important to everyone before we move ahead together in planning for future facility needs in LWSD. The FAC will use your thoughts to create a new facility strategy that will align with the district’s Strategic Plan. The FAC will make recommendations to help accommodate our rapid enrollment growth and continue to provide quality learning environments. The Superintendent and School Board will consider these recommendations as it plans for future ballot measures to fund construction. More: bit.ly/LWSDFAC

Lake Washington School District’s (LWSD’s) 2019-20 Budget has earned the Association of School Business Officials International (ASBO) Meritorious Budget Award (MBA). This award promotes and recognizes excellence in budget presentation in school districts. LWSD has received this award three years in a row. LWSD is the only district in the state of Washington to receive this award.

“We want our budget documents to be understandable, accessible, and easy to read,” noted Dr. Jane Stavem, Superintendent. “Our staff works hard to make this happen, and we’re proud to receive this award for a third year as we continue to focus on effective ways to communicate with our community.”

To view the 2019-2020 budget, visit our website: bit.ly/LWSDBudgetAward

January 22 at 11:21 PM ·

“In spite of temporary victories, violence never brings permanent peace.” —Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

In his pursuit of freedom, Martin Luther King Jr. never lost sight of his commitment toward nonviolence. Students at Juanita Elementary School learned on Friday how their PRIDE characteristics (Problem solving, Respect, Integrity, Diligence and Empathy) applied to Dr. King.

Music teacher Lesley Paige led students in the songs “Candle of Peace” and “Ev’rybody Ought to Know What Freedom Is.” Students also learned about Mahatma Ghandi, who influenced King, and Rosa Parks, who played a pivotal role in the Montgomery bus boycott against racial segregation.

Juanita’s Associate Principal, Edith Brumant, sang part of “Lift Ev’ry Voice and Sing,” which is often called “The Black National Anthem.” It was written as a poem by NAACP leader James Weldon Johnson and set to music by his brother John Rosamond Johnson is 1899.

If your child cannot arrive at school safely on time tomorrow, please notify your school office and they will report it as an excused tardy.

Six LWSD middle school girls, also known as Jelly Jolts #39887, have teamed up with Molly Moon's Homemade Ice Cream – Redmond to create a braille menu for those who are blind and visually impaired.

“We want to spread awareness that [blind and visually impaired] people are out there and there needs to be more done for them,” said Varnika Bhargava. “We want to create more accessibility in the state for people who are blind and visually impaired.”

Do you or your high school student have questions regarding the college process? Find Your Fit is a college-prep program geared towards supporting parents and students in what could be a stressful time for both the parents and the students. Mary Pat O'Neil helps break it all down by offering steps involved in applying to college and also how to find the perfect college fit.

Our next workshop, Apply to College 101, will be at Lake Washington High School on January 23 at 7pm.

Visit www.lwsf.org/findyourfit to register for this free class.

post_text:
A team of 24 young athletes and partners, with and without disabilities, represented Eastlake High School (EHS) at this year’s Special Olympics Robotics Championship. The event took place at the Seattle Center on November 17 with 36 teams competing in four different fields. The EHS team, with their Wolf Pack Green robot, earned third place. They also won the Spirit Team and Rising Star awards. Students at EHS lined up to send-off the team before the competition.

Watch a short video of the send-off: bit.ly/EHSRoboticsSendOff

Read more: bit.ly/EHSRobotics

post_text: Fourth grade students at Robert Frost Elementary School are learning about the life cycles of salmon. The students saw Coho and Chinook salmon up close during a visit to the Issaquah Salmon Hatchery on November 8. During a tour, they learned about salmon habitat and how the hatchery operates. They also learned how to tell the difference between Coho and Chinook, and whether a fish was male or female. Read more: bit.ly/FrostSalmon

They did not quit.”

“Thank you!” exclaimed students at Peter Kirk Elementary School during their Grand Opening Ceremony and Ribbon Cutting on October 24. School Board Vice President Mark Stuart said, “Kirk Elementary reflects your family and your neighbor’s commitment to support you and your education by giving you a better place to learn and grow.”

The rebuilt and enlarged school was approved by voters in 2016 and has space for 690 students.

Lake Washington School District’s (LWSD) official October 1 student enrollment was 31,106 students. This represents 1,124 more students than last year’s October 1 count. LWSD is now the second-largest district in the state, behind only Seattle Public Schools.

“Our enrollment growth is reflective of our dynamic communities,” said Dr. Jane Stavem, Superintendent. “We are grateful for the ongoing support of our entire school district community as we continue to address the needs related to our rapidly growing student population. The growth of our school district presents unique challenges and opportunities as we address current over-crowding and future expansion possibilities.”

Read more: bit.ly/LWSDEnrollment19

Lake Washington School District hosted representatives from the U.S. Department of Education and the Washington State Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction on October 28 as part of the 2019 #GreenStridesTour. This year’s tour, themed “Whole Child, Whole School Sustainability,” runs October 28-30 in Washington schools.

Lake Washington School District was named a 2019 U.S. Department of Education Green Ribbon School District Sustainability Awardee for its efforts to reduce environmental impact and costs; improve health and wellness; and teach environmental education. Two sites and three schools were featured on the October 28 tour: Carl Sandburg Elementary/Discovery Community School and Peter Kirk Elementary School.

(CC: Kirkland, WA - Government, U.S. Department of Education Green Ribbon Schools, Peter Kirk Elementary School PTSA, Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI), U.S. Department of Education)

post_text:
Students have found that when they take a class with Karen Knerr, they learn more than just math. The Kamiakin Middle School teacher is one of 16 Seattle Heroes in the Classroom to be recognized during the 2019 NFL season. Symetra and the Seattle Seahawks will recognize her, in a customized Seahawks jersey, during the November 3 game where she will be an honored guest.

Knerr teaches middle school math despite being fully deaf. A parent recently told Symetra that “Mrs. Knerr helped my daughter recognize that she is capable of working through challenges through resourcefulness and tenacity; the life skills and personal development she acquired are priceless and will travel will her for the rest of her life.”

As part of this award, Knerr received a $2,000 donation to benefit her classroom, two tickets to the Seahawks vs Buccaneers game, a pre-game VIP sideline experience, an in-game HawkVision spotlight and a “Heroes” award certificate.

post_text: Congrats to Belle Brandenfels for being honored as Washington Interscholastic Activities Association’s Athlete of the Week! Belle is the captain of the cross country team at Lake Washington High School (LWHS). She is recognized for her run time at Nike's 2019 Hole in the Wall XC Invitational, also known as the Pacific Northwest’s premier cross country meet. There she ran 18 minutes and 36 seconds in the 5,000 meter, making her the record holder at LWHS. Way to represent LWSD, Belle! 🙌 💪 🏃‍♀️ 👟

Second graders in Mrs. Emily Andrews’ class recently celebrated Indigenous Peoples’ Day at Redmond Elementary. Students learned the “Since Time Immemorial” curriculum, including traditional and modern life of West Coast Salish people. They also listened to Native American music. Afterward, they watched a video about a Raven Dance and even learned how to do a Pow Wow dance themselves! Check out these photos from their fun-filled day.

post_text:
College Board has new ordering deadlines, late fees and cancellation fees for the 2020 Advanced Placement (AP) exams. To meet the College Board ordering deadlines, LWSD students will register and pay for AP exams from Monday, October 14, 2019 through end of last lunch on Friday, October 25, 2019. We encourage all students wanting to take May 2020 AP exams to complete the registration and pay for their exams during this October registration window.

For students who may still be deciding in October if they want to take AP exams in May, a LATE AP Exam Registration window will be open from Tuesday, February 18, 2020 through end of last lunch on Thursday, February 27, 2020. Students who register during the late AP Registration window will incur a $50 per exam late fee in addition to the $96 per exam fee.

Students who register during the late AP Registration window will incur a $50 per exam late fee in addition to the $96 per exam fee.

post_text: Lake Washington School District is putting the power of technology and innovation in the hands and fingertips of our students. Thanks to funding from the voter-approved 2018 Capital Project Levy, each fifth grader across the district has access to Microsoft Surface Go’s while in class. The versatile laptops enable students and teachers to work together on anything from math problems to research for essays. Fifth-grade teachers are learning new instructional delivery strategies to enhance and transform the teaching and learning environment through the use of mobile devices. The students also learn life skills that will help them with their future education or even in the workplace by learning how to be responsible for the devices and by using real-world applications and programs. Thank you, voters, for helping make every student future-ready!

JHS is one of five Washington schools on the tour.

Lake Washington School District students continue to score well-above the state average in all areas tested by the Smarter Balanced Assessments.

“Our students continue to achieve at high levels and we celebrate the hard work of teachers and students as we review these indicators,” noted Dr. Jane Stavem, Superintendent. “However, we also know we continue to have persistent achievement gaps that require a laser-like focus on the ways we support all students to do their best learning.”

post_text: Hundreds of volunteers came out on Community Serve Day Sunday, August 25, to get their neighborhood schools ready for the upcoming school year. Volunteers of all ages handled a variety of tasks including power washing the blacktop and play structure, replacing the mulch around the shrubs, and repainting maps in play areas. Teachers were especially grateful for the help they received getting the classrooms ready, as the volunteers helped with a variety of tasks so the teachers could devote more time to planning their lessons for the first week of school.

For the fifth year in a row, the LWSD Leadership Team packed Pantry Packs as part of its August meetings. This year, the team packed 756 Pantry Packs in 23 minutes and 33 seconds on August 7. In 2018-19, a total of 25,700 packs were delivered to 45 LWSD schools, which benefited 800 food insecure students each week. The food for the packs was donated by Sodexo, LWSD’s Nutrition Services provider.

To learn how you can help, visit: lwsf.org/pantrypacks

post_text:
Lake Washington School District (LWSD) was accepted today into the League of Innovative Schools, a national coalition of forward-thinking K-12 school districts organized by Digital Promise, a nonprofit organization with the mission to accelerate innovation in education and improve the opportunity to learn for all through technology and research.

“We are very excited to be selected as a member of this National Network of Innovative School Districts,” said Dr. Jane Stavem, LWSD Superintendent. “Joining the League of Innovative Schools allows us to elevate our practice as we develop and expand opportunities for our students by collaborating with other great districts from across the nation.”

Read more: bit.ly/LWSDDigitalPromise

Lake Washington School District added 14 new photos.
July 29, 2019 at 9:58 PM ·

Kevin Chandler is a math teacher who inspires his students to go beyond a textbook to become worldly problem-solvers and critical thinkers. He presents complicated problems with ease – ditching the jargon and concepts. Instead, he connects with students on a real human and personal level – making math fun and exciting – and providing clever strategies to tackle each problem with confidence.

“I take great pride in meeting my students where they are in their math education,” said Chandler. “I work with them to find out what can be done to clarify and simplify difficult concepts, so they can master the learning targets routinely.”

Chandler teaches Algebra 1 Booster, an enrichment summer school…

post_text: Calling all high school students and parents! College application season is here. Come learn about the steps involved in applying to college and how to find the perfect college fit. This workshop explains everything you'll need to know to be college-ready. August 15, 2:30 – 4:30 p.m., at the Sammamish Library, (825 228th Ave SE, Sammamish). Space is limited. RSVP: lwsf.org/findyourfit
shared_text:
Lake Washington Schools Foundation
July 22, 2019 at 6:48 PM ·

Due to popular demand, we have added another Apply to College 101 workshop!

Apply to College 101 is designed for high school students and their parents/guardians. Not only will you learn the steps involved in applying to college, but also how to find the perfect college fit. Topics include:
· Understanding the different types of colleges
· The cost of college
· The 5 (possible) parts of a college application: high school transcript, standardized tests, activity list, letters of recommendation, essays
· How to create a balanced college list and why it is important
· Great college resources
· Why students need to visit colleges and how/when to do it
· Financial aid and scholarships
· Understanding the business of college: acceptance rates and yield
· Early Decision, Early Action – what do they mean?
...and more!

Join us on August 15 from 2:30-4:30pm at the Sammamish Library. Free to attend but limited spots available so get yours today! www.lwsf.org/findyourfit

post_text: Students from Environmental and Adventure School went on a sailing expedition on June 4 as part of the school’s yearly campout at Bowman Bay. On the sailboat, students learned about oceanography and orienteering while gaining new skills in community building, teamwork and communication. Throughout the week, students also had the opportunity to study marine biology, ethnobotany, outdoor cooking and more.

post_text: Calling class of 2020! Do you need help with your college application and essays? Lake Washington Schools Foundation is hosting a FREE College Application and Essay Workshop on August 5, 2 – 4 p.m., at the Redmond Library, (15990 NE 85th St.). Take advantage of this opportunity to boost your college application. Space is limited, so register early!
shared_text:
Lake Washington Schools Foundation
July 12, 2019 at 12:06 AM ·

Does your rising senior (Class of 2020) need some help with their college applications and essays?

Have no fear! Mary Pat of True Fit College Counseling and Lake Washington Schools Foundation is putting on a College Application and Essay Workshop on August 5 from 2pm-4pm at the Redmond Library.

Topics covered:
· Tips for creating and completing college application platforms (Common App, Coalition App)
· What is the role of the essay in college admissions (5 possible parts of the college application)
· What colleges are looking for in an essay
· How the college essay is different than most writing high school students have done
· How not to write an essay
· How to write an essay
· Discovering your stories
· The importance and difficulty of supplemental essays

...and so much more!

Limited space is available so hurry and claim your spot today! www.lwsf.org/findyourfit

post_text: Eleven student teams competed in the Investor Round of the 2019 LWSD Teen Startup Challenge event on June 8. At the event, students pitched their business plans to a panel of distinguished local CEOs and executives, competing for the grand prize of $2,500, courtesy of the Lee Johnson Family, and a spot on the stage at the Greater Kirkland Chamber’s Investor Sharks Northwest event this November. Eastlake High School student Ron Pechuk took home the grand prize this year for his company, Extentek, which produces a device to aid the visually impaired.

post_text: Evergreen Middle School (EMS) sent a team to the National Science Bowl this year, held April 26-30 in Washington, D.C. The team made up of Kaaviya Uthirapandian, Sri Sai Tejas Varma Pakalapati, Medha Venkatapathy, Harish Krishna Kumar and Purab Shah, competed in several rounds. The team finished first in their division before moving onto the double elimination stage of the competition, where they tied for ninth place. Read about their achievement: bit.ly/EMSScience

post_text:
Congratulations to the Lake Washington High School class of 2019! At their June 17 graduation ceremony at Alaska Airlines Arena (at University of Washington), LWSD Superintendent Dr. Jane Stavem said, "Graduation is one of my favorite events to attend. It’s a way for our community to publicly recognize and witness the conferment of a degree and a right of passage. And to now offer this group of young adults as our very best gift to the world.”

Student speaker Grace Lanning said, "Tomorrow is Tuesday, June 18, 2019. The day after we graduate high school. And for me, for me tomorrow is just another day to be grateful for the joys of all our yesterdays.”

Senior class president Anna Captain said, “In this millennium, I see the promise and the passion in this room and I know it is enough to build something different. Something good.”
